## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement — `Thread.Abort` forcibly kills a thread that exceeds a time limit.

**Key change:** `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. Replace with cooperative cancellation via `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // Overload without token for backward compatibility
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(work, timeout, CancellationToken.None);
    }

    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token);
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Task-based model; uses thread pool |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(cts.Token)` | Cancellable wait (.NET 6+) |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.CancelAfter(timeout)` | Cooperative cancellation |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No equivalent needed |

### Critical pitfall: cancellation is cooperative now

The original `Thread.Abort` **forcibly injected** an exception into the thread. The new model only works if `work()` checks for cancellation. If `work()` is a tight CPU loop or blocking call that never checks the token, **it will not stop**.

**Fix:** Pass the token into the work function:

```csharp
// Change the signature to accept a token-aware delegate
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout,
    CancellationToken externalToken = default)
{
    using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
    cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
        return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Callers must cooperate:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in largeCollection)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // ← checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Other pitfalls to watch for

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always `using var cts = ...`; leaking causes timer leaks |
| **`Thread.Sleep` ignoring cancellation** | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch at the top-level; the `when` filter above distinguishes timeout vs. external cancel |
| **Expecting instant stop** | Cancellation only fires at the next `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` call — add checkpoints in loops and between expensive operations |
| **Truly uncooperative code** (e.g., third-party library) | Move to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout — this is the only safe forced-termination left in modern .NET |
